{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616611"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:05:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:05:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16407"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16407"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.07,0.22,0.37,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9098"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75961"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9098"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16407"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61462"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7115"},{"type":"tags","id":"10404"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21609"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75961"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe frontal lobe is the largest lobe of the human brain and is responsible for many higher-order functions. It extends from the central sulcus to the frontal pole and contains several specialised functional areas.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following functions is least likely to be affected by isolated damage to the frontal lobe?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Executive function","Motor planning","Emotional regulation","Olfaction","Speech production"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe frontal lobes are critical for higher-order cognitive functions and motor control. \u003Cstrong\u003EExecutive function\u003C/strong\u003E, including planning, decision-making, and working memory, is primarily mediated by the prefrontal cortex. Damage to this area can result in significant impairment in these domains.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMotor planning\u003C/strong\u003E is controlled by the premotor cortex and supplementary motor area in the frontal lobe. Damage can lead to difficulties in coordinating complex movements and motor sequences.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmotional regulation\u003C/strong\u003E involves the orbitofrontal cortex and other frontal regions. Frontal lobe damage often results in personality changes and difficulties in emotional control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlfaction\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily processed in the temporal lobe, specifically in the piriform cortex and amygdala. While olfactory information does reach some frontal areas, the primary processing occurs elsewhere, making it the function least likely to be affected by isolated frontal lobe damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpeech production\u003C/strong\u003E involves Broca\u0027s area in the inferior frontal gyrus. Damage to this region can result in expressive aphasia, characterised by difficulty in speech production while maintaining comprehension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The frontal lobes are involved in executive function, motor control, speech production (Broca\u0027s area), emotional processing, and personality.","Olfactory processing occurs primarily in the temporal lobe, specifically the piriform cortex and amygdala.","The frontal lobe contains key functional areas including the primary motor cortex, premotor cortex, and prefrontal cortex."],"references":["Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Catani M. The anatomy of the human frontal lobe. Handb Clin Neurol. 2019;163:95-122. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-12-804281-6.00006-9. PMID: 31590750.","Chayer C, Freedman M. Frontal lobe functions. Curr Neurol Neurosci Rep. 2001 Nov;1(6):547-52. doi: 10.1007/s11910-001-0060-4. PMID: 11898568.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Hoffmann M. The human frontal lobes and frontal network systems: an evolutionary, clinical, and treatment perspective. ISRN Neurol. 2013;2013:892459. doi: 10.1155/2013/892459. Epub 2013 Mar 14. PMID: 23577266; PMCID: PMC3612492."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61462"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16407"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61462"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T18:30:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T18:32:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9098"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75961"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"